{{Infobox library | library_name = Lillian Goldman Law Library | library_logo = | image = Yale Law Library Reading Room vertical.JPG | caption = Reading Room of Lillian Goldman Law Library | country = [[United States]] | type = [[Law library]] | established = | location = [[New Haven, Connecticut]] | num_branches = | collection_size = 800,000 volumes | annual_circulation = | pop_served = | budget = | director = | num_employees = | website = [http://library.law.yale.edu/ library.law.yale.edu] }} The '''Lillian Goldman Law Library in Memory of Sol Goldman''', commonly known as the '''Yale Law Library''', is the [[law library]] of [[Yale Law School]]. It is located in the [[Sterling Law Building]] and has almost 800,000 volumes of print materials and about 10,000 active serial titles, in which there are 200,000 volumes of foreign and [[international law]] materials. The library was named after a USD $20 million donation made by Lillian Goldman, widow of real estate magnate [[Sol Goldman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/21/nyregion/lillian-goldman-80-yale-law-school-donor-and-advocate-for-women-s-education.html|title=Lillian Goldman, 80, Yale Law School Donor and Advocate for Women's Education |website=nytimes.com |date=2002-08-21 |accessdate=2017-04-15}}</ref>
It is also well known as the place where [[Bill Clinton]] and [[Hillary Rodham]] met for the first time.<ref name="My Life">{{Cite book|last=Clinton |first=Bill |title=My Life |publisher=[[Random House]] |year=2004 |isbn=1-4000-3003-X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Bernstein |first=Carl |authorlink=Carl Bernstein |title=A Woman in Charge: The Life of Hillary Rodham Clinton |year=2007 |publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf]] |location=New York |isbn=0-375-40766-9}}</ref><ref name="Living history">{{cite book |last=Clinton|first=Hillary|title=Living History|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Books/story?id=127895&page=1|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>
==Facilities== The library is contained within five stories on the eastern wing of the Sterling Law Building, completed in 1931 and designed by [[James Gamble Rodgers]]. The library's main reading room, named for the Class of 1964, is located on the library's third story. Employing the [[Collegiate Gothic]] style used throughout the law school campus, it is modeled after the [[King's College Chapel, Cambridge|King's College Chapel]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name="Pinnell">{{cite book |first=Patrick L. |last= Pinnell |title=The Campus Guide: Yale University |publisher=Princeton Architectural Press |year=1999 |page=98 |ISBN=1568981678}}</ref>
In addition to the library's main body, two annex levels of bookstacks are contained below [[Beinecke Plaza]], and infrequently used items are contained in the Yale University Library Shelving Facility in [[Hamden, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Guide to the Lillian Goldman Law Library In Memory of Sol Goldman |date=September 2011 |publisher=Yale Law School |url=http://www.aallnet.org/sections/all/storage/mktg-toolkit-2013-docs/yale-library-guide.pdf |accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref>
